	<article class="post-634319 post type-post status-publish hentry category-asset-management-2 category-investment-banking category-legal category-markets tag-credit-and-debt tag-european-central-bank tag-government-bonds tag-gross-william-h tag-mather-scott-a tag-pimco-pacific-investment-management-company tag-stocks-and-bonds per-gross-william-h per-mather-scott-a-2 des-credit-and-debt des-government-bonds des-stocks-and-bonds org-european-central-bank org-pimco-pacific-investment-management-company news_keywords-debt-2 news_keywords-european-central-bank news_keywords-government-bond news_keywords-pimco-pacific-investment-management-company-2 news_keywords-scott-a-mather news_keywords-stocks-and-bonds news_keywords-william-h-gross" id="post-634319">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/other-topics/asset-management-2/">Asset Management</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">New Manager of Pimco&#8217;s Flagship Fund Sticks to View on Low Interest Rates</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Landon Thomas Jr.			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-23T12:35:29+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 23, 2014 8:35 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 23, 2014 8:35 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/23/new-manager-of-pimcos-flagship-fund-defends-european-bond-holdings/" data-title="New Manager of Pimco&#8217;s Flagship Fund Sticks to View on Low Interest Rates" data-description="At an investment conference, Scott A. Mather, who now oversees Pimcoâs Total Return Fund, defends its outsize holdings in European government bonds and other high-yielding securities.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/24/business/dbpix-pimco-spain/dbpix-pimco-spain-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/24/business/dbpix-pimco-spain/dbpix-pimco-spain-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/24/business/dbpix-pimco-spain/dbpix-pimco-spain-blog480.jpg" id="100000003192910" width="480" height="286" alt="The stock exchange in Madrid on Thursday. Scott A. Mather of Pimco said that Spanish bond yields would converge with those of Germany."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="286"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The stock exchange in Madrid on Thursday. Scott A. Mather of Pimco said that Spanish bond yields would converge with those of Germany.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sergio Barrenechea/European Pressphoto Agency</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/to-restore-confidence-in-economy-a-test-of-europes-banks/">Regulators Are Gauging Europeâs Banks, and Remedy May Sting a Little (Oct. 17, 2014)</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><span id="t11h1s" class="update">Updated, 11:01 a.m. | </span></webonly>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. &#8212; In an environment of growing concern about trading conditions in global debt markets, the new manager of the largest bond fund in the world â Pimcoâs Total Return Fund â defended his outsize holdings in European government bonds and other high-yielding securities at an investment conference on Wednesday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In one of his first public appearances since he succeeded <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about William H. Gross." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/g/william_h_gross/index.html?inline=nyt-per">Bill Gross</a> last month as the fundâs lead manager, <a href="//www.pimco.com/EN/Experts/Pages/ScottMather.aspx">Scott A. Mather</a> emphasized that there would be no changes to Pimcoâs house view that interest rates would remain low in a weak global economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In such an environment, Pimco has argued, there is a strong case to made for investing in riskier securities, be they high-yield corporate bonds in the United States or debt securities issued by Mexico or Brazil. T<span style="color: #222222;">he Total Return fund also has large holdings in inflation-protected Treasury bonds, which are very actively traded and provide a substantial liquidity cushion for the portfolio.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Matherâs presentation at a <a title="ETF.com Conference" href="//www.etf.com/inside-fixed-income-conference/index.html">conference for exchange-traded bond funds, put on by ETF.com</a>, came after a series of cautionary notes struck by investors.</p>
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many bond managers remarked about how difficult it had become to sell higher-yielding bonds and how worried they were that funds with large positions in hard to sell securities would have a difficult time getting rid of these bonds in a market panic.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAll the liquidity has been sucked out of the market by <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Reserve System." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_reserve_system/index.html?inline=nyt-org">the Fed</a>,â said Robert G. Smith of Sage Advisory Services, an investment firm based in Austin, Tex. âThere is just too much in the hands of too few â it really keeps us sleepless at night.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Smith said there was $7.6 trillion outstanding in United States corporate bonds, yet the market traded only $20 billion a day.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For some time now, regulators <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/16/pimco-and-other-big-firms-could-face-liquidity-crisis-in-risky-bonds/">have warned about</a> this so-called liquidity illusion, whereby too many infrequently traded bonds end up in the hands of a small number of large asset managers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Matherâs presentation was straightforward and low key, and it <a href="//www.riabiz.com/a/4934666637279232/bill-grosss-stage-antics-leave-morningstar-conference-goers-gobsmacked">lacked the theatrics</a> â if not the energy â that defined Mr. Grossâs public appearances.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Asked about his big bet on Europe, Mr. Mather said he was convinced that the <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about European Central Bank" href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_central_bank/index.html?inline=nyt-org">European Central Bank</a> would buy government bonds to spur growth and that Italian and Spanish bond yields would converge with those of Germany.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Mather was also pressed about the fundâs ability to exit its large positions in inflation-protected <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about treasury securities." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/t/treasury_department/treasury_securities/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier">Treasury securities</a> and mortgage investments that were not guaranteed by the government. Mr. Mather said he had no concerns about these holdings or Pimcoâs ability to exit from them.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He said that Pimco was a small part of the high-yield market, which he said was actively traded.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;This is not a systemic problem we are talking about, &#8221; he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">More broadly, he made it clear that Pimco had sufficient reserves of easy to sell investments that could be liquidated in order to meet redemption demands.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThere are sections of the bond market that will overshoot,â he said, referring to a possible selling spree. &#8220;That is a risk â but its also an opportunity.â</p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/to-restore-confidence-in-economy-a-test-of-europes-banks/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/21/business/dbpix-eurobank5/dbpix-eurobank5-thumbWide.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="Regulators Are Gauging Europeâs Banks, and Remedy May Sting a Little" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/to-restore-confidence-in-economy-a-test-of-europes-banks/?ref=dealbook">Regulators Are Gauging Europeâs Banks, and Remedy May Sting a Little</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By JACK EWING and LANDON THOMAS JR.</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">Echoing a U.S. move from 2009, the European Central Bank is taking a hard look at banksâ books, but its findings may further rattle the markets.</p>
			</div>
			
	</div>
